title: Cow's Dual Bowden MK2 (for Prusa i3 Mk2 clones)

description.text:
Cow's Dual Bowden Extruder MK2 (Ramshead)

Couldn't find a dual extruder I liked, so I made my own! This is designed for Prusa i3 clones, especially those who use the Prusa i3 MK2's universal X mount.

Fan nozzles in the images are not the latest versions!
Will upload BOM first chance I get!

Features:

  • Universal 22.5mm Prusa i3 X Mount
  • E3D v6
  • Bowden Extrusion
  • Inductive Probe
  • Independent Z-adjustment
  • Single or dual extrusion
  • Optional PWM Turbine for part cooling
  • Standard E3D fan cooling

Known issues and planned features for MK3:

  • Z-adjustment bends on the base plate. Keep an eye on this while adjusting.
  • Will split the base plate so that each extruder and z-probe can be removed without disassembling the Z adjust.
  • Major adjustments to the Z-adjust accuracy and ease of use coming.
  • Major adjustments of the turbine shroud coming.

Assembly tips:

  • I used two springs from ink pens for the Z-adjust to save money
  • Attach the "Fixture" to the "Base", but do not tighten until the Z distance is adjusted.
  • Adjust primary extruder's Z distance only until the nozzle touches the bed, then use the software Z offset in your firmware to align accurately.
  • Don't trust model measurements for tool offsets! Calibrate manually with test prints. Minor flexing in the fixture adds up.

Let me know if and how it works for you!

description.text:
Corner clips for the Tevo Tarantula with 2mm, 2.5mm, 3mm, 4mm, 5mm or 6mm thick glass. They will probably fit other printers but can't test. My main purpose with this design was to get rid of those ugly paper clips.
The left side clips are flush with the glass so the nozzle won't catch when the printer homes, the right side clips are raised above the glass by 2mm to clamp it down. You may get away with printing 4 of the flush ones but I've not tried.

To fit the glass slot it into the right side, you may need to pull the left clips back a bit to push the glass down.

For those worried about heat I only print in PLA and having my bed at 65C with my PLA corner clips is no issue. If you want to print anything in ABS having PLA corner clips probably isn't a great idea ;)

If they don't quite work for you feel free to remix them to add/subtract 1mm here or there.

UPDATE - I'm being inundated with requests for changes to the size etc. I have not got time or the patience to do this for every different size glass. I will not be doing any more updates on this and will be making the fusion 360 files available instead. Do what I did and watch a few youtube videos, you'll soon get the hang of it.

title: R3D Flsun I3 Mod Kit Part 1

description.text:
R3D Flsun I3 Mod Kit

This is part 1 of 3 of my collection of mods for the Flsun I3 printer. This is the most important mod out of all three parts. These mods will help stabilize the X and Z axis and fix z wobble and most layer line issues. It does require hardware upgrades, but they are relatively inexpensive.

Use the photo with the ruler as a guideline for spacing. Also, there is about 2-3mm of space between the leadscrew and the motor rod inside the coupler.

Don't forget to change the Z_MAX_POS to 255mm like I did and have your first 250mm print stop at 220! :)

*Update 5/24/2017 - added photos of a recent print and for the dimensions for the anti-backlash nuts

*Update 6/29/2017 - Printing smoothly at 100mm/s. With all the mods in this series, I can easily go up to 120mm/s. https://youtu.be/6qQ_azx2F1E?t=16

Notes on Printed Parts:

Top Rods Holder -- These are the top brackets which are modified from the original to have a tighter fit and a hole for the leadscrew.
Lead Screw Wobble Brackets -- These use skateboard bearings to keep the leadscrew in a fixed axis and aligned with the top rods holder.
XZ Carriages fitted for Anti-Backlash Nuts - Left & Right -- These will fit anti-backlash nuts and igus delrin bearings. You can use the steel linear bearings but you may have to sand the holes out a bit.
XZ Carriages Original Fittings - Left & Right -- To fit steel bearings and regular nut.
Z Limit Switch Mount -- Modified to fit over the Lead Screw Wobble Brackets and for better stability.
Hotend X Carriage -- Adjusted fan mounts for better alignment. Modified belt holes for easier mounting. Modified to fit igus bearings.

Required Hardware to go along with the printed parts:

  • 2x 370-400mm Lead Screws. I used 400mm because I couldn't find any 370.
  • 2x Skateboard Bearings
  • 2x Anti-Backlash Nuts - see photo for specific dimensions.
  • Fiberglass reinforced belt (optional but highly recommended) It will have less stretch over time.
  • 4x Igus Delrin Linear Bearings (optional) You can use the original steel bearings.

I have included the original XZ brackets so you don't have to use the anti-backlash nuts but in order to get the full benefit, I recommend using the modified version.

description.text:
R3D Flsun I3 Mod Kit

This is part 3 of 3 of my collection of mods for the Flsun I3 printer.

Spool Holder

Stubby Parts Cooler -- While I think the fang cooler is a better choice, if you don't have a working parts cooler now, you may want to print the stubby to help print the fang as it can be difficult without a cooler. Or, print very slow with an external fan pointed at your bed.

E3D v6 Heatsink Fan Shroud (40mm) & 5015_40 Fang Combo -- You may need to use the Stubby cooler to get the fang printed properly. This combo also requires a 40mm fan for the heatsink and 4 x M3x16mm hex screws.

  • Aluminum Bed Carriage Plate (RepRap or Winhao Duplicator version).

I was on the quest for a simple, but cheap pop up style FPV racing gate. The cheapest ones I could find were $35 + shipping, with some being more than $60 each. After doing some research, I found a design by user "sekthree" here: http://imgur.com/a/23jRd and used some of his ideas to come up with this! I designed the 3d printed elbow and it holds the gate together very well.

The great thing about this gate design is that it's super light weight, it's easy to store and carry (you can easily twist it similar to soccer pop up goals), and it holds up very well. Finished dimensions of the gate are approximately 5ft wide by 3'10" high or so.

Update 6/14/2017: After using these gates for about a month, I have made a few improvements! I added a small cut out / notch so can more easily tie the string to these- it shouldn't slip around. Where I fly, the wind is very strong, so I added a hole to the back of the elbow that you can use to stake these gates down. I am using a Coleman 10" stake, but any stake about that size or smaller should work. These improvements are in the v2 file. I also recommend printing this in a PETG filament. On one of my gates, the PLA got a bit hot in the sun (90+ degree day) and bent. PETG should't do that!

Update 5/15/2017: Check out these gates in action! Youtube video here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EseufUs_-Sg

Cost Estimate- The total estimated total cost for this project with the materials I list is about $15-$22 to make one initial gate. If you buy another set of the fiberglass poles, and cut the materials similar to what I did, you will be able to make 3 gates for around $30-35.

Rods:
http://www.harborfreight.com/3-16-inch-x-33-ft-fiberglass-wire-running-kit-65326.html

Parts needed:

  1. For $10, you can buy the fiberglass rods linked above from Harbor Freight. You will need to use 6 rods per gate. There are 10 rods in the container. If you buy two containers, you can make 3 gates (18 rods). Each rod is 33 inches long. Very important: I strongly recommend putting electrical some tape around where the rods connect, because the brass fittings will easily break if they are loose. They come loose pretty easily, too.

  2. 3d print the race gate elbows. These will be a fairly tight fit, but will hold the rods securely. I included the OPEN SCAD source code, so if you need different rods you can change the design. If you only need a little more room, just change the inner diameter variable (mm). If you need a lot more room (more than a few mm) you may need to update the model to scale it appropriately. (~$1 of filament)

  3. Light string or rope. Cut it about 5ft 6 inches, or just enough to make a loop on the elbows, running the string from elbow to elbow so there is 5ft of string in between. ($1 for rope)

  4. A few metal stakes to hold down the elbows. I always have wind blowing, so the stakes are definitely recommended. ($1 each)

  5. Race Gate material: I used a shower curtain, mine was $8 at a dollar store. You can find them for cheaper (as low as $1 on clearance). Make sure the material feels sturdy. If I recall, it was 72 inches wide by 70 inches long. This was enough material for 3 gates. Also pay attention to the pattern, if it has one. You will need 105" length total for these gates. For mine, I was able to use the pattern and cut into 3 pieces (info below).

I also recommend a bright colored shower curtain so you can see it easily. Blue is probably not the best choice (as pictured here) but white, yellow, or pink would definitely stand out. You may also want to experiment with materials and try something like a ripstop nylon fabric.

Finished dimensions of race gate material: 105" length x 4" width

How I cut my material:
Middle section: 66 1/2 inches x 8 inches
End Pieces: 19" x 8 inches

Your cutting/sewing may vary depending on the shower curtain you use. Just make sure you have 105 inches or so width x 4 inches. You may be able to save sewing multiple pieces together by picking a solid fabric that has a length > 105". Get creative!

Sewing the seams:

  1. Sew the middle section and end pieces together so it creates on continuous piece (creating a 105" total length, 8 inches width).
  2. Fold the material in half (folded you should now have 105" x 4")
  3. Sew a continuous seam for fiberglass rod at the top: Between 1/2 to 5/8" at the top
  4. Sew a continuous seam where the pieces meet at the fold

Storing the gate:
There are two options for storing the gate.
Option 1. Simply "twist" and the gate will flatten down. It's small enough to fit in your trunk or on a wall when collapsed using the twist method.
Option 2. Disassemble the gate by removing the 3d printed elbows, remove the fabric, unscrew the rods. This will only take a few minutes and you can collapse it down to something very small. You should be able to fit all 3 gates, material, and 3d printed parts in the original container that the fiberglass rods came in.

title: Gottingen 765 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (39.61g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
The drone propeller has been designed by using the Gottingen 765 airfoil coordinates (used on the Messerschmitt Me 163 Komet). All tests were done on the Drone Propeller Thrust Tester Results can be inspected below.

It was printed slowly, by using a 0.2 extruder nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The final part was cleaned using a Precision Knife

After this, I then got to finish the propeller using a 400 grit sandpaper.

These are the thrust readings for some voltage values (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 8.45 grams
  • 2V => 11.29 grams
  • 2.5V => 22.59 grams
  • 3V => 39.61 grams

The files I included contain all pictures relevant to the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the STL files and the SLDPRT files. If you want to play with the propeller, make sure you have a couple of 8520 coreless motors.

You should use the SLDPRT files, just in case you want to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Note: Airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
A clean, compact lamp designed for LED light bulbs. Please don't try to use this for anything other than low-heat LED bulbs, it was not designed to handle incandescent.

I wanted a small light source I could keep on the bookshelf behind my reading chair to house a Phillips Hue Bulb. I have had this powered on, with maximum brightness, for a week solid now and the temperature of both the base and the shade are both barely above room temperature. I feel confident in putting this up for public use along with the disclaimer of again, please only use low heat bulbs.

The base will print very cleanly with only supports needed for the small cup. Print this piece with the large cavity upwards and the small socket down. I used ABS at 70% infill and had no issues with the overall balance of the lamp.

The bottom cap prints with the same material as the base, nothing fancy here. For me it is a friction fit, no glue necessary.

The top shade I printed using clear polycarb, but that was only due to it being the only clear I own. I'd be comfortably using abs for this as well. My settings were 0% infill, 4 solid bottom layers (for the top of the shade) and 1 perimeter. I also cranked up the extrusion multiplier by 5% to help give me a softer, textured appearance.

I harvested the lamp socket from a spare gooseneck lamp I have however it looks to be the same as: this one.
